(see also: CWDSUP-700)

When multiple groups are specified in an svn authz file for a repository path and the principal belongs to more than one of those groups the group that actually gets used for the permission is the one that occurs last in the list of groups returned from Crowd's {{findGroupMemberships}} SOAP method.

This is (obviously) difficult behavior for the user to understand or modify.

Suggested change: Make the user's effective authz level that of the most permissive group they belong to. For example, if the SVNAuthz file looks like

{noformat}
[/path]
@group1=r
@group2=rw
{noformat}

and the principal belongs to both {{group1}} and {{group2}}, then their effective permission would be "rw" because that is the most permissive permission.

From a customer:
{quote}
We have a requirement, which is probably specific for MS Active Directory: When we authenticate a user, the current ldap protocol (standard) does not read the "log on to..." information. This information specifies which workstation the user can logon to. All other workstations are disabled for the user and just some are enabled. We need to authenticate it in our webapp and/or other servers (in Java). Can Crowd help with it?
{quote}

The {{CrowdCredentialsProvider}} currently wraps all calls to the {{SecurityServerClient}} with the following boilerplate:

{code}
try
{
    client.doStuff();
}
catch (Exception ex)
{
    log.error(ex.getMessage(), ex);
}
{code}

Apart from the fact that logging (particularly at error level) and swallowing exceptions is bad practice anyway, there are a bunch of other problems with this approach.

# We swallow actual configuration or environmental problems that should be propagated to the user so they may be actioned. These should be reported to the system admin and/or support.
# Application level exceptions (like an incorrect password) are logged as an error in our logs - no, no, no!!!

A better approach is:
{code}
try
{
    client.doStuff();
}
catch (RuntimeException ex)
{
    throw ex;
}
catch (InvalidPasswordApplicationException ex)
{
    return false;
}
catch (CrowdSystemException ex)
{
    throw new RuntimeException(ex);
}
{code}

where the thrown RuntimeException may have a more useful signature. (Given that the interface the CCP implements is from OSUser this signature is purely for stacktrace prettiness reasons, not to be handled anywhere explicitly.)

Given these changes, there is no need for this class to log at anything higher than INFO level.

There's a bug in the parsing of the SVN auth file. Whitespace isn't stripped from the last token token on the line, so if you have an entry that looks like

{noformat}
[/]
@my-group = rw 
{noformat}

with a space after the 'rw' on the line, it will not be matched properly when working out the authz.

see CWDSUP-618

